        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1978-01-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1978-01-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="362"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d362">
                <head>362. Letter From Ambassador-at-Large and Special Representative for
                    Non-Proliferation Matters <persName corresp="#p_SG_1">Smith</persName> to the
                    President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BZ_1"
                        >Brzezinski</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d362fn1">Source:
                        Carter Library, National Security Council, Institutional Files, Box 4,
                            <gloss target="#t_PD_1">PD</gloss>–08 [4]. Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1978-01-13">January 13, 1978</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear Zbig:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I believe it is essential that the President approve these shipments of
                    highly-enriched uranium to Europe quickly. All of these cases represent <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> commitments to existing projects. They are not
                    new commitments which our policy seeks to avoid. As you know, the Europeans are
                    extremely sensitive to any signs that the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> is
                    using its nuclear fuel as pressure to achieve <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                    objectives in <gloss target="#t_INFCE_1">INFCE</gloss> or to force them to
                    renegotiate the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_EURATOM_1"
                        >EURATOM</gloss> Agreement. While I have tried to assure the <pb facs="0954"
                        n="923" xml:id="pg_923"/> French and others that this is not the case, the
                    Europeans read the already long delay associated with <gloss target="#t_HEU_1"
                        >HEU</gloss> approvals (none since last May) as <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                        >US</gloss> pressure tactics. Our non-proliferation efforts, as well as our
                    overall political relationships with alliance countries, would be best served by
                    prompt approval.</p>
                <p>The Romanian case is also significant in view of our efforts to improve relations
                    with Eastern Europe. In my view the proliferation risk here is negligible. Also,
                    this case involves a firm <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> commitment.</p>
                <p>Sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SG_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Gerard Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d362fn2">
                            <persName corresp="#p_SG_1">Smith</persName> signed the memorandum
                                “<persName corresp="#p_SG_1">Gerry Smith</persName>.”</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
